Here's why I think altcoins will outperform #bitcoin during Q2 and Q3 of this year.

Time for a thread ğŸ§µ https://t.co/9ZjyItiWcb

1) First of all, in recent weeks we had an accumulation of bad news and events. But during this time, it was very remarkable to see how altcoins kept up versus Bitcoin. Even during the heaviest of news and fear in the market, altcoins held up strong compared to Bitcoin.

2) The $BTC.D or bitcoin dominance only went up with 4%, from 39.4% to $43.4% right now. 

That's not what you would expect during an uncertain period like the past few months where a war broke out, stock markets fell, inflation rose dramatically,... https://t.co/I9eUVXrI8p

3) Add to that that the accumulation of bad events happened at a technical point of support, where you would expect the $BTC.D to bounce anyway, no matter the events. The bounce isn't as strong as the past 2 on this same level. In total, the ~40% level has now been tested 3 times https://t.co/FPB8jJHCkM

4) I personally expect the bounce to continue for a few more weeks, up to ~45%. There it will experience historic resistance and trendline resistance. I expect it to make a lower high there and continue its way down towards 40% again. https://t.co/oDwMQq7kyB

5) When we test the 40% level again, it will be the 4th test of this level... That might be too much to see another bounce. Given the relative weakness of this bounce, when all factors are in favor of a strong $BTC.D bounce, we can expect the dominance to fall below this 40%.

6) Also the fact that a descending triangle is shaping up gives me the feeling we'll see the $BTC.D fall below 40% towards an all-time low. Last all-time low was 35% and I'm pretty convinced we'll see a bitcoin dominance below 30%.

7) When we have a look at $ETH / $BTC we see the inverse structure of the $BTC.D, which makes sense because a lot of the altcoin market cap is Ethereum. 

An ascending triangle is shaping up, with higher lows and resistance at 0.08. I expect $ETH to break above that level in Q3. https://t.co/rRPB8vFoVa

8) Ethereum leads the altcoin market and that's been the case for as far as I remember. Bitcoin has been weak this entire cycle, barely claiming its moments of fame throughout it. I expect this trend to continue, and Ethereum pulling the rest of the altcoin market with it.

9) We have not seen an altseason yet like the ones we have seen in 2017. Back then, it didn't matter what the altcoin did or the quality of the project. Simply everything pumped and had its time. The altseasons we have seen in this cycle, are different. The pumps were selective.

10) That brings me to the fact that I think we haven't seen the 'real altcoin mania' yet, where not only L1s, NFTs or metaverse projects pump, but all the rest too. 

I also think that the retail fomo during this cycle has been much different to previous cycles.

11) This brings we to the comparison between the last altcoin cycle and the one now. We had a similar descending triangle during '15-'16 and '18-'20 with a breakout and re-accumulation. I think we're now in the re-accumulation period that we also saw during 2017. https://t.co/Qz8sef8L29

12) Don't get me wrong, I don't think we'll see the same increase in altcoins as we have seen in 2017, that would simply not be realistic. The altcoin market matured and last cycle this started from basically 0 and had its initial hype and speculation. It's different now.

13) But I do believe that everything points towards a great increase for altcoins in Q2 and Q3, at least outperforming $BTC. I expect the altcoin market to top out somewhere between $3T and $5T. That's a 3x - 5x from now.

14) This of course in the scenario that we don't get new serious developments macro-economic wise. There are always black swan events possible. But it feels that the world's financial markets are at peak fear right now.
15) Thank you for attending my TED talk. Don't forget to follow me.

Now that's inverting... https://t.co/bgAH8owR0R

If the ratio between the 10y and the 2y inverses, and goes below 0%, it'd have a problematic impact on the market liquidity and doesn't predict anything good for the economy and financial markets.

Note that an inverted US yield curve has predicted every recession since 1960!! https://t.co/L6n0UYThCY

When these yield curve inversions happen, usually the FED will loosen its monetary policy... 

But since we're in a situation of raging inflation and the FEDâ€™s fund rate is already at zero, it feels like they are totally trapped to do something about this. https://t.co/05NoXjzr0t

IMPORTANT: The % of $BTC not being moved for over a year is increasing. 

We are now ~6 months after a major turnaround like we only saw twice before. We saw it in 2018, ~6 months before the #bitcoin bottom and in 2014, ~9 months before the price bottom was in. https://t.co/KTOvewcqFN

Now, what does this mean? Historically we see the $BTC price bottom 6-9 months after this turning point. People are not longer willing to sell (or even move) their bitcoin and are simply holding it. Mainly because they think price increases are coming or accumulation is here.

So, this indicator turns around during a period of bear market. After 6-9 months of this indicator going up, the #bitcoin price bottoms. 

We are now 6 months after this turning point so we can say that the bottom should be in or close and that we're in an accumulation stage.

Personally I don't think this indicator has peaked yet. This means that the accumulation phase can still continue for some time. We're currently at 63% while historically the peak turning point to the downside is a bit higher.

Once it has reached its high, a bull market starts. At that point more people are willing to sell their #bitcoin into the strong price action again. For now, it means we're in accumulation, but this indicator tells us the bottom of this bear market/accumulation phase is in.
